	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=3165><span id= >Shawndy</span></a><br><span id=notbold>2 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default [1.66]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Oh and what you meant to say was &quot;header and footer&quot;... which isn't really necessary in a TCP/IP packet either.<br><br>The original modem code included start and stop bits, which MIGHT be what you're thinking of... since they were analog signals and needed to know when the next byte was beginning... oh and they were optional...<br><br>TCP/IP packets DO have headers... and I suppose you could put a &quot;footer&quot; or &quot;ender&quot; on the packet if you were so inclined... but EQ packets are not 256 bits.&nbsp;&nbsp;They are different sizes depending on what the packet is actually for.  <br><br>If you would like further information, please search the web.  Just because a junior high school computer science teacher tells you it's so... doesn't make it so. *grin*</p>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
