	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=3165><span id= >Shawndy</span></a><br><span id=notbold>2 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default [1.66]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Actually, the assumption that an entire packet would be sent just to submit a signed character is false.<br><br>And to help you further... 256 bits of information would generate a number greater than the number of atoms in the universe.<br><br>What you were looking for is 8 bits of information... 8 bits generates a number between 0 and 255 (256 total numbers) unless you use one bit for the sign (+/-) in which case you have 7 bits which can give you a number between 0 and 127 (128 total numbers).<br><br>And it has nothing to do with packets, other than a character (8bits) was used to store the data instead of a word (16bits) or double-word (32bits).<br><br>&quot;It is better to have people think you're an idiot than open your mouth and remove all doubt.&quot;<br>- Mark Twain, if memory serves, was credited with this saying... smart guy</p>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
